# Commit Message Conventions

Clawperator follows the [Conventional Commits](https://www.conventionalcommits.org/) specification with some project-specific adaptations.

## Format
```
<type>: <description>

[optional body]

[optional footer(s)]
```

## Types
- `feat`: New feature or enhancement (correlates with MINOR in semver)
- `fix`: Bug fix (correlates with PATCH in semver)
- `refactor`: Code changes that neither fix bugs nor add features
- `doc`: Documentation changes only
- `test`: Adding or updating tests
- `chore`: Maintenance tasks, dependency updates, etc. (not refactoring)
- `style`: Code style/formatting changes
- `perf`: Performance improvements

## Breaking Changes
- Indicate breaking changes with a `!` before the colon
  - Example: `feat!: change folder creation API`
- Or use a `BREAKING CHANGE:` footer

## Guidelines
- Use present tense ("add feature" not "added feature")
- Try and keep first line under 50 characters
- Description should complete the sentence "This commit will..."
- No period at the end of the description
- Leave one blank line between title and body
- Use body to explain what and why vs. how
- Wrap body text at 64 characters for readability

## Examples
```
feat: add Polish language support
fix: prevent racing of requests
refactor: simplify drag state management
doc: update cursor rules
test: add folder creation tests
chore: update Kotlin to 1.9.0
feat!: change folder creation API
```
